ftfA&UNY\nLEfwmimr\ntaken n company of naturalists to Alaska with\nhim aa hla guests Ha had had a delightful time\nwith the scientists and they had profited much\nin a knowledge way by the trip to comparatively\nnew fields 1 found that Mr Harrlman waa keen\nly Interested in birds trees shells flowers\nstones and mammahC and that ho knew and ap\npreciated nature in all Ita forma That waa the\nonly time I ever saw H H Harrlman but from\nwhat ho said during tho two hours and a half\nspent In hia ear that winter nifiht I was not at\nall surprised whan I found out that ho had pro\nvided a fond tor sooioglcal research\nAcroca Lafayette square due west from the\nCosmo club is tho vacant Decatur mansion\nThis house was built by Commodore Stephen De\ncatur In tha year 1910 and it was from Ita por\ntals that ho went forth one year later to meet hie\ndeath at tha hand of Jamu Barron also n naval\nofficer who had challenged Decatur to n duel It\nla American history and tha circumstances arc\nknown to nil but it might bo amid that it waa\nBarron who waa in command of the United\nStates ship Chesapeake at the time it was over\nhauled by tho British ship Leopard and eytivd\nfor alleged deserters from tho British navy\nBooks have been written about Lafayette\nsquare but tha stories that are told about tha\nmen whose statues are In tea square and abont\nthe men who lived In the honeee surrounding It\nare endless and not nil of them perhaps have\nfound their way into print The statue of Lafay\nette was erected at one corner of the square not\nlong after tha statue of Andrew Jackson had\nbeen put In place in tho center of tha square\nprovided a square con be said to have n center\nLafayette visited America in 1925 and even to\nday one hears occasionally of some living person\nwho remembers hla visit\nNot long ago there dlod in Chicago at her\nhome on Elm street the aged Mrs Davidson\nSho was born In Charleston 8 C Her H-\"\nname waa Ancrum she waa a granddaughter of\nCol William Washington a first cousin of George\nWashington It was William Washington wbo\nat tee battle of tea Cow pens fought a hand-to-hand\nfight with Colonel Tarleton of tho British\nforces Colonel Washington succeeded In cutting\noff the thumb of Tarleton\u2019s sword hmii Ud\nthen there waa interference which separated tha\ncombatants\nLafayette waa n strong personal friend of WU-\nWashington and whan he visited Charleston\nin the year 1925 he waa n guest at tha Ancrum\nresidence Mrs Ancrum the mother of Mrs Da\nvldaon being n daughter of Colooel Washington\nMrs Davidson than a child six or eight yean\nold remembered tho visit perfectly and kept\nuntil she died a promt which Lafayette hod\ngiven to her tho grandchild of his old friend and\ncomrade in arms\nThera lsno states of Washington In Lafayette\naqnore though ou day then may be for tt la\nsaid to bo poaalhlo that Andrew Jackson may bo\nput elsewhere and Georgs Washington may take\nhis place Tho nearest physical approach ao to\napeak teat one gets to tho lint pnsMent la La\nfayette square is in tha White House which\nfronts ft It may not ha generally known that tha\nWhite House was completed before Washington\ndied It wu only a few days before Ma death\nas Washington tradition bu tt that Georgs and\nwmfUi Washington walked through the recently\ncompleted White Homo to give their approval\nor disapproval ns ft may be of tho arrangement\nof tho rooms It is passible that that visit to\ntho capital wu tea last one which the Fsther\nof hla Country made tor It wu only a short time\nafterward that ha died at his euuntiy coat Mount\nVernon\nBeforuneo to Mount Vernon brings to mind\ntea fact that there is Bring in Washington today\nan aged nun named John I one who Is tho only\nliving person who over uw Cengs Washington\nNow Inasmuch u tea Father of his country died\nin yean ago this may seam to be something\npretty clou to n false statement on Its face but\nIt la tho troth nevertheless\nWhen John Lana wu n small boy the driver\nof a stage teat ran between Washington and\nMount Vernon asked the lad if ho wanted a ride\nand tho answer wu a hasty climbing np to the\nBeat of honor\u2019 by tho driver Tho boy made tho\ntrip all the emy to Mount Vernon and arrived\n(here Just u they were removing tea body of\nWashington from tho old tomb to tho new an\nIn order to mnko certain that tho remains had\nnot been tampered with by ghouls who not long\nbefore had broken Into tho old tomb the anffln\nwu opened ml John Loco aged ten wu fitted\nup to lock on the face of the father of his Coun\ntry Mr Lena today la tha only person who\n(arrives of tba ilitlo company which wu greasoj\nat uw traMfor of Uu tody\nAged Woman Found Dead\nSt Louisw\u2014 dfn Henrietta Dana\n74 yean old widow of Hercules\nDenman millionaire tobacco manu\nfacturer and tho daughter of tho late\nGen S D Sturgis U 8 A wu found\ndead in her home In Clayton HL\nLouis county Her physician said she\ndied of hurt disease She is survived\nby two sons John Dausman of St\nLouis and William Dausman of\nUnion Ma Her father wu a civil\nwar hero and famous Indian fighter\nBrothers Died at Bamo Hour\nAurora 111\u2014 -Two telegrams\nannouncing tha' death of a brother\nwere filed at tha same time Om wai\nsent from Aurora to David Smith at\nWatson Ma announcing tho death\nof hla brother Cspt C K Smith Au\nrora millionaire and tho other wav\nfrom Watson to tho Aurora brother\ntelling of tho death of David Each\ntelegram told that the brother had\ndied at 1:99 o'clock\nAriiona Town Burped\nBlabee Arior-Naca a town of UN\npeople located on tha Mexican line\nnine miles south of Blabee in this\ncounty wu destroyed by fire accord\ning to information received hero The\nWestern Union operator reported that\nhe would be forced to flee for his life\nml shortly afterward tho wires parted\nFireman Hurt in Explosion\nHouston Tex\u2014 While fighting a fin\nin tha debris of the Houston Transfer\nCa\u2019a building which wu burned 35\nfiremen were badly burned and scalded\nby an explosion of carbide Nona\nwu fatally Injured\nPrefers Death to Cell\nWinchester Ky\u2014 C L Frailer who\nras sentenced to five yean in tho pen\nitentiary for larceny committed sui\ncide in hla cell in the Jail hero by tak\ning carbolic add A negro \"trusty\" ad\nmitted htriui bought tec drug\nSayc Dun's Review Wlfh Little to En\ncourage Speculative Enterprise\nat Present Tima\nNew York\u2014 R G Dun\u2019s weekly re\nview says:\n\"With crops aggregating large in\nquantity and value in spite of the re\nduced yield of spring wheat with pol\nitics becoming so intense and uncer\ntain u to make enterprise timid and\nwith railroads and shippers engaged\nIn n dispute over rates tho business\noutlook is mixed trade reaction being\nplain in soma important directions\nwhile at tho same time then arc\nstreaks of progress and activity\n\"It is u n whole n watting situa\ntion with little to encourage specu\nlative enterprise until conditions now\ndoubtful or unsettled become more\nclearly defined\n\"Interest in Iron and steel hu cen\ntered chiefly in predictions of an early\ngeneral reduction of prices of finished\nsteel products which have been dis\ncussed and the effect hu been dls- -quieting\nnotwithstanding denials from\nwell-informed aourcea Soma conces\nsion! have been granted from time to\ntime of late but tt hu boon officially\nIntimated that no change of policy\nwill ho undertaken by tho large pro\nducer Now buslneu hu diminished\nbut aside from railroad material n\nproduction continues in finished lines\n\"in tho dry goods market tho im\nprovement In silks and ribbons is con\ntinued and n few mills arc running\nfull and overtime In woolens and\nworsteds the demand u n whole in\nbettor- yet orders arc no null and\nirregular that mills aro unable to re\nsume operations in n largo way\n\"Cottons an generally in moderate\ndemand and throughout tho trad\nthem is n desire to confine orders to\nactual requirements\n\"Footwear conditions show n alight\nimprovement hut the actual volume\nof trade continues moderate Tho\namount of new business however is\nsomewhat larger Thera is n decided\nImprovement in the demand for aolo\nleather with larger tales especially\nof oak aole\"\nBusiness Failures\nYorfc\u2014 Bradstreet\u2019s\nNew\nsays:\nBuslneu failures in the United\nStates for tke week ending Septem\nber 22 were IN against 210 last week\n171 in the like week of 1909 2C7 in\n1908 160 In 1907 and 165 in 1906\nBuslneu failures In Canada for the\nweek number 22 which compare with\n20 for last week and 37 In the like\nweek of 1909\nWheat Including flour exports from\nthe United States and Canada for tea\nweek ending September 22 aggregat\ned 1683669 bushels against 2171052\nlast week and 2973601 this week last\nyear 2 or the II weeks ending Sep\ntember 22 exports are 17534362 bush\nels against 25031023 in the corre\nspondlug period last year\nCorn exports for tho week are 299\n266 bushels against 174079 last week\nand 94419 in 1909 For the 12 weeks\nmdlng September 32 corn exports aro\n3092262 bushels against L235A61\nlast year\nv","height":"26408","width":"17376"}}
